\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Statistical Mechanics: Mid Term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Emmanuel Flores
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
Mar 3, 2024
\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
Let’s go back to the cyclical heat engine we’ve analyzed in the last two
 assignments.
 In this problem we’re going to work out the Clausius integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\oint\frac{\delta Q}{T}$
\end_inset

.
 We already know from HW #2 how to evaluate the contributions from the isotherma
l legs.
 It remains to deal with the linear ones.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
As the system moves along the path, P,V, and T all change.
 Show that, for a monatomic ideal gas:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int\frac{\delta Q}{T}=\frac{3}{2}nRf\left(p_{A},p_{B}\right)+\frac{5}{2}nRf\left(V_{A},V_{B}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and specify the form of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a,b)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using this result, calculate the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\oint\frac{\delta Q}{T}$
\end_inset

 for the entire cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What does your result imply regarding the reversibility of the cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compare your conclusion to what we concluded on HW #2 from our analysis
 of the efficiency of the engine.
 Do they agree? If not, what do you think might account for the discrepancy?
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
Let's start:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We know that for a monoatomic ideal gas, the internal energy is just a function
 on the temperature, and even more, we know the functional relation, which
 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U=nC_{v}T\implies dU=nC_{v}dT,
\]

\end_inset

and even more, in virtue of the second law of thermodynamics, we have that
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
dU & =dQ-pdV,\\
dQ & =dU+pdV.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and we also know that for an ideal gas, the following functional relationship
 (ideal gas equation) holds
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
pV=nRT,
\]

\end_inset

and now, we have everything we need to prove the proposition.
 By definition, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dQ}{T}=\int_{A}^{B}\frac{1}{T}\left(dU+pdV\right),
\]

\end_inset

then, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dQ}{T} & =\int_{A}^{B}\frac{1}{T}\left(nC_{v}dT+pdV\right),\\
\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dQ}{T} & =\int_{A}^{B}\frac{nC_{v}dT}{T}+\int_{A}^{B}\frac{pdV}{T},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and making use of the ideal gas equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dQ}{T} & =\int_{A}^{B}\frac{nC_{v}dT}{T}+\int_{A}^{B}\frac{nRpdV}{pV},\\
\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dQ}{T} & =nC_{v}\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dT}{T}+nR\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dV}{V},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and from the previous relation we have, after integration, that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dQ}{T}=nC_{v}\ln\left(\frac{T_{B}}{T_{A}}\right)+nR\ln\left(\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and again, making use of the ideal gas equation, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dQ}{T}=nC_{v}\ln\left(\frac{p_{B}}{p_{A}}\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}}\right)+nR\ln\left(\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and from the properties of the logarithm, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\left(xy\right)=\ln x+\ln y$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dQ}{T} & =nC_{v}\ln\left(\frac{p_{B}}{p_{A}}\right)+nC_{v}\ln\left(\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}}\right)+nR\ln\left(\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}}\right),\\
\implies & =nC_{v}\ln\left(\frac{p_{B}}{p_{A}}\right)+\left(nC_{v}+nR\right)\ln\left(\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

but for monoatomic gases, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{v}=\frac{3}{2}R$
\end_inset

, thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{A}^{B}\frac{dQ}{T}=\frac{3}{2}nR\ln\left(\frac{p_{B}}{p_{A}}\right)+\frac{5}{2}nR\ln\left(\frac{V_{B}}{V_{A}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and therefore, the functional form of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the logarithmic function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now, for this second part we have that for both isothermal processes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{nR}\int\frac{dQ}{T}=\ln\left(\frac{V_{2}}{V_{3}}\right)-\ln\left(\frac{V_{1}}{V_{4}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and for the first linear process we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{nR}\int_{2}^{3}\frac{dQ}{T}=\frac{3}{2}\ln\left(\frac{p_{3}}{p_{2}}\right)+\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{3}}{V_{2}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and using the ideal gas equation we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{nR}\int_{2}^{3}\frac{dQ}{T}=\frac{3}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{2}}{V_{3}}\right)+\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{3}}{V_{2}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and for the other linear process
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{nR}\int_{4}^{1}\frac{dQ}{T}=\frac{3}{2}\ln\left(\frac{p_{4}}{p_{1}}\right)+\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{4}}{V_{1}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and again, making use of the ideal gas equation we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{nR}\int_{4}^{1}\frac{dQ}{T}=\frac{3}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{1}}{V_{4}}\right)+\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{4}}{V_{1}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

thus, the integral over the whole cycle becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{nR}\oint\frac{dQ}{T}=\ln\left(\frac{V_{2}}{V_{3}}\right)-\ln\left(\frac{V_{1}}{V_{4}}\right)+\frac{3}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{2}}{V_{3}}\right)+\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{3}}{V_{2}}\right)+\frac{3}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{1}}{V_{4}}\right)+\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{4}}{V_{1}}\right),
\]

\end_inset

and this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{nR}\oint\frac{dQ}{T} & =\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{2}}{V_{3}}\right)+\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{3}}{V_{2}}\right)+\frac{1}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{1}}{V_{4}}\right)+\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{4}}{V_{1}}\right),\\
\frac{1}{nR}\oint\frac{dQ}{T} & =\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{2}}{V_{3}}\right)-\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{2}}{V_{3}}\right)-\frac{1}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{4}}{V_{1}}\right)+\frac{5}{2}\ln\left(\frac{V_{4}}{V_{1}}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and from this, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{nR}\oint\frac{dQ}{T}=2\ln\left(\frac{V_{4}}{V_{1}}\right)\neq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now, from the previous equation, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\oint\frac{dQ}{T}\neq0,
\]

\end_inset

but we know that if the above closed integral is zero, then the process
 is reversible, thus, in this case the process is irreversible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Finally, in the assignment #2, we found that the efficiency of this engine,
 was lower that a Carnot engine, which by construction is reversible, and
 even more, we know that all reversible engines share the same efficiency,
 thus, because the efficiency was lower that implied the process was irreversibl
e, and here, we prove the same statement, but using a different approach.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Problem
A typical battery for an internal- combustion-engine vehicle is a 12 Volt
 lead-acid battery, with a capacity of around 50 Ampere-hours.
 (Since an Ampere is a Coulomb per second, 50 Ah is a number of Coulombs.
 It tells you the amount of charge the battery can push through a circuit
 before it’s fully discharged.) The fundamental reaction is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Pb}+\text{Pb}\text{O}_{2}+4\text{H}^{+}+2\text{SO}_{4}^{2-}\rightarrow2\text{PbSO}_{4}+2\text{H}_{2}\text{O}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
How much electrical work can the battery provide before it’s fully discharged?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If you want to know how much electrical work can be provided per mole of
 reactants, which thermodynamic parameter should you look at? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If you want to know how much total energy is released per mole of reactants,
 which thermodynamic parameter should you look at? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using the table, what are the values of the quantities mentioned in 2 and
 3? Are they the same? If not, where does the energy go or come from to
 account for the difference? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Based on your answer to 4, is the entropy of the products higher or lower
 than the entropy of the reactants? By how much (per mole)? Does your answer
 agree with what you find in the table? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Each time the reaction occurs, two electrons are released by the reactants,
 flow through the external circuit, and then recombine with the products.
 Knowing this, what is the voltage provided by one such battery cell? A
 12 V battery has multiple cells arranged in series to give the full voltage.
 How many?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How many moles of SO42- would you expect the battery to contain? Does the
 order of magnitude of your answer seem reasonable? Why?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
Let's begin:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We know that the voltage of the battery is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $V=12$
\end_inset

 Volt, and the capacity of the battery is 
\begin_inset Formula $50$
\end_inset

 Ah, thus the energy or electrical work will be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W_{e} & =12\times50\left[\text{VAh}\right],\\
W_{e} & =600\text{\left[Wh\right],}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

thus the battery could provide a maximum amount of electrical work given
 by 600 Watts-hours 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For this we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G$
\end_inset

 is associated with the spontaneity of a physical or chemical change, and
 this, is also associated with the amount of work that a system can perform
 on the surroundings, but let's elaborate a little more on this; by definition,
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=H-TS,
\]

\end_inset

thus, under constant pressure and temperature 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta G=\Delta H-T\Delta S,
\]

\end_inset

and from the above expression we can see that the first term on the RHS,
 under some conditions, could be interpreted as energy released to the environme
nt, and therefore used to work.
 On the other hand, the second term in the RHS is interpreted as increasing
 the entropy, thus, if we consider a process in which the system is always
 in equilibrium, in such a way that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta S\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

, we can associate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G$
\end_inset

 with the maximum amount of possible work.
 Therefore, I will look up for the change in Gibbs free energy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We should look for the change in enthalpy; 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the total amount of thermal energy at a constant pressure, thus we can
 associate 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta H$
\end_inset

 as the difference in enthalpy between the products and reactants of a chemical
 reaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Here's the full reaction and a table with the information provided for this
 problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Pb}+\text{Pb}\text{O}_{2}+4\text{H}^{+}+2\text{SO}_{4}^{2-}\rightarrow2\text{PbSO}_{4}+2\text{H}_{2}\text{O},
\]

\end_inset

 
